data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The Cosmos SDK is fundamentally async-only; EF Core previously shimmed synchronous calls by blocking on async operations internally. That opt-in is now gone.

Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — no configuration workaround.

**Affected calls in your code:**

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Fix

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This will ripple `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.) — that's unavoidable and intentional. The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync calls, but Cosmos never truly did.
